# Overview

Cursor Rule: FE-albania (Discover Albania Frontend)

1. Stack, Tooling & Versions (DO NOT UPGRADE BY DEFAULT)
   Languages & Runtime
   TypeScript: Use the existing TypeScript setup (typescript@^5.8.3), no strict-mode migration unless explicitly requested.
   JavaScript/TS Interop: allowJs is enabled; prefer TypeScript for all new code. Only touch .js files if necessary for a specific bug.
   Frameworks & Core Libraries
   React: Use React 18 (react@^18.3.1, react-dom@^18.3.1).
   Routing: Use React Router 7 (react-router@^7.9.4, react-router-dom@^7.9.4).
   State & Data Fetching:
   Prefer React Query v5 (@tanstack/react-query@^5.83.0) for async server state.
   Use local component state (useState, useReducer, useMemo, useCallback) for UI-only state.
   Do not introduce any new global state libraries (Redux, Zustand, Jotai, etc.) without explicit instruction.
   Backend Client: Use Supabase only through the existing client:
   src/services/api/apiClient.ts with @supabase/supabase-js@^2.86.0.
   Build & Tooling
   Bundler/Dev Server: Vite 5 (vite@^5.4.19) with @vitejs/plugin-react-swc@^3.11.0.
   Linting:
   Uses ESLint 9 with typescript-eslint and React Hooks rules via eslint.config.js.
   Do not change ESLint config or rules unless explicitly requested.
   Styling Tooling:
   Tailwind CSS 3 (tailwindcss@^3.4.17, tailwindcss-animate@^1.0.7, @tailwindcss/typography).
   PostCSS/Autoprefixer as currently configured.
   UI/Component Libraries:
   Radix-based shadcn-style UI under src/components/ui/\*\*.
   MUI (@mui/material, @mui/icons-material, @mui/x-date-pickers) already in use – do not add new design systems.
   Other helpers (Embla, Keen Slider, Lucide, Sonner, React Spinners, Recharts, etc.) should be used in a way consistent with existing patterns.
   Version Policy
   Do NOT upgrade library versions, React, TypeScript, Vite, or any tooling unless the task specifically asks for upgrades.
   When adding imports, reuse existing libraries only; do not add new dependencies without explicit instruction.
2. High-Level Architecture & Boundaries
   Overall Architecture
   Single-page app (SPA) with:
   Entry: src/main.tsx (createRoot + <App />).
   Routing & Providers: src/App.tsx (React Router, React Query client, toast providers, Tooltip provider, Speed Insights).
   Layering (Conceptual)
   UI Layer: src/components/** (reusable components), src/pages/** (routed screens).
   Hooks Layer: src/hooks/** (shared stateful logic, e.g., useSearchFilters).
   Domain Types: src/types/** (entity and DTO typings).
   Data/Service Layer: src/services/api/** (Supabase access and domain-specific services).
   Utilities: src/lib/** (generic utilities).
   Routing Boundary
   All routing is defined in src/App.tsx via <BrowserRouter> + <Routes> and nested <Route>s.
   Do not introduce other routers or scattered routing definitions.
   Protected routes must go through the existing ProtectedRoute component.
   Always add new routes in App.tsx, above the catch-all "\*" route as indicated by the existing comment.
   Service/Data Boundary
   All Supabase calls must be made through service functions in src/services/api/** using the shared apiClient.
   Do not call createClient or apiClient directly from components/pages; encapsulate in services.
   Business logic around entities (hotels, apartments, cars, users, auth) belongs in service modules, not in components.
   UI & Domain Separation
   Pages (src/pages/**):
   Compose components, call hooks (including React Query hooks) and service functions.
   Contain page-level layout and orchestration but minimal domain logic.
   Components (src/components/**):
   Presentational or small container components reused across pages.
   Should receive data and handlers via props instead of reaching into services directly whenever possible.
   Hooks (src/hooks/**):
   Encapsulate reusable state and behavior (e.g., complex filter logic, query coordination).
   May call services, but must expose a clean interface (data, loading, error, callbacks).
3. Critical / High-Risk Files & Folders
   These areas require extra caution; treat them as stable APIs and avoid structural changes unless explicitly requested:
   App Entrypoints
   src/main.tsx
   src/App.tsx (routing, providers, and top-level app shell)
   Routing/Access Control
   src/components/ProtectedRoute.tsx
   Supabase Client & Auth
   src/services/api/apiClient.ts
   src/services/api/authService.ts
   src/services/api/userService.ts
   Core Domain Services
   src/services/api/hotelService.ts
   src/services/api/apartmentService.ts
   src/services/api/carService.ts
   src/services/api/storageService.ts
   Shared Hooks & Search Logic
   src/hooks/useSearchFilters.ts
   Shared Types
   Entire src/types/** directory (especially hotel.types.ts, apartment.type.ts, car.types.ts, user.types.ts, search.types.ts).
   UI Foundations
   src/components/ui/** (shadcn-like primitives; treat as mostly read-only except for necessary bug fixes).
   Dashboard Shell
   src/components/dashboard/hsidebar.tsx and src/pages/dashboard/dashboard.tsx.
   Rules for these files:
   Do not:
   Rename, move, or significantly refactor them without an explicit, justified request.
   Change their external API (exported functions, types, or component props) without updating all usages and clearly explaining the impact.
   Allowed changes (by default):
   Localized bug fixes.
   Non-breaking additions (e.g., adding a new service method, adding optional props, strengthening runtime checks).
   Adding comments and small refactorings that do not alter external behavior.
4. Project Structure & How to Add New Features
   Existing Structure (follow this)
   src/pages/home/**: Home-facing pages (landing, search results, reservations, culture details, etc.).
   src/pages/dashboard/**: Admin/provider dashboard pages, segmented by domain (Hotels, Cars, Apartments, Users, etc.).
   src/components/home/**: Reusable components for the home/marketing side.
   src/components/dashboard/**: Layout and components for the dashboard (e.g., hsidebar, ImageUpload, mapPicker).
   src/components/ui/**: Low-level reusable UI primitives (buttons, cards, modals, etc.).
   src/services/api/**: Service modules per domain (hotels, apartments, cars, users, auth, storage).
   src/hooks/**: Shared hooks.
   src/assets/**: Static assets (images, icons).
   src/types/**: Types per domain.
   src/components/home/data-map/**: Map components and static map data.
   Adding a New Feature (Pattern)

1) Decide the area
   User-facing: create a new page under src/pages/home/YourFeature.tsx.
   Dashboard/admin: create under src/pages/dashboard/<Domain>/YourFeature.tsx.
2) Register the route
   Add a <Route> in src/App.tsx within the correct area (<ProtectedRoute> for authenticated dashboard, outside for public pages).
3) Add services (if needed)
   Create or extend a service file under src/services/api/yourDomainService.ts:
   Export domain functions (getX, createX, updateX, deleteX, and any search/filter functions).
   Optionally export a default object aggregating those functions (copy existing pattern from hotelService or apartmentService).
4) Add types
   Add or extend domain types in src/types/yourDomain.types.ts (follow naming like CreateHotelDto, UpdateHotelDto).
5) Add UI components
   Shared or reusable components: place in src/components/home or src/components/dashboard as appropriate.
   Keep components small, focused, and pass data via props.
6) Add hooks
   For complex shared state or logic, add a custom hook in src/hooks/YourHookName.ts:
   Use useSearchFilters as a reference for structure and error handling.
   Naming & Conventions
   Components: PascalCase file name and component name (HotelsPreview.tsx, Hsidebar.tsx).
   Hooks: camelCase starting with use (useSearchFilters.ts).
   Services: camelCase exported functions (getAllHotels, createApartment) and optionally a default object hotelService/apartmentService.
   Types: PascalCase with clear suffix (Hotel, CreateHotelDto, HotelFilters).
   Routes: Keep consistent naming and capitalization with existing paths; do not arbitrarily change existing paths.

5. Data Fetching, State Management & Async Safety
   React Query Usage
   Use useQuery, useMutation, and QueryClientProvider configured in App.tsx.
   Prefer React Query for:
   Fetching lists or details from Supabase (e.g., hotels, apartments, cars, users).
   Any data that can be cached and shared across pages.
   Query functions should be service functions from src/services/api/\*\*.
   Handle isLoading, isError, and error states in UI components (see HotelsPreview.tsx for a pattern).
   Avoiding Anti-Patterns
   Do NOT:
   Mix raw fetch/axios calls in components for domains already covered by services.
   Duplicate domain logic (e.g., reimplement filters already found in useSearchFilters or service-level searchX functions) unless truly necessary.
   Introduce global mutable singletons other than QueryClient in App.tsx.
   Async Safety & Error Handling
   In services:
   Always handle Supabase error responses:
   Log context and rethrow as Error or the original Supabase error.
   Return safe defaults where appropriate (e.g., data || [] for list fetches).
   Wrap multi-step flows (upload + DB insert) in try/catch and provide useful error messages, similar to createHotel and createApartment.
   In components/hooks:
   Assume services may throw; wrap await calls in try/catch or rely on React Query’s error surface.
   Surface user-friendly error messages via existing toast/toaster components where appropriate.
   Do not introduce unhandled promises; always await or explicitly handle Promise rejections.
6. Null Safety & Type Safety
   TypeScript Configuration
   Current tsconfig.json has:
   strictNullChecks: false
   noImplicitAny: false
   Do NOT change these compiler options without an explicit migration request.
   Code-Level Practices
   Despite relaxed compiler settings:
   Prefer explicit, non-any types for new functions, props, and service returns.
   Always account for null/undefined from Supabase (e.g., data || [], Hotel | null).
   Use narrowing and optional chaining instead of unsafe assumptions.
   Avoid casting with as any; use precise interfaces/types in src/types/\*\*.
7. Styling Conventions
   Preferred Styling
   Default to Tailwind CSS classes in JSX for layout and styling (see Index.tsx, HotelsPreview.tsx).
   Use existing shadcn-style components in src/components/ui/\*\* where appropriate instead of hand-rolling primitives.
   Conditional & Utility Classes
   Use existing helpers like clsx and Tailwind utilities; do not introduce new class-manipulation libraries.
   Avoiding Anti-Patterns
   Minimize inline styles, except for small one-off cases (e.g., Dashboard title styles); prefer Tailwind classes.
   Do not introduce additional CSS frameworks or design systems (e.g., Bootstrap, Chakra, etc.).
8. Acceptable vs Unacceptable Patterns
   Acceptable
   Minimal, focused changes that:
   Fix a specific bug.
   Add a well-scoped feature following existing patterns.
   Extend service modules with new functions without breaking existing ones.
   Using existing hooks/services:
   Use useSearchFilters for property search features instead of duplicating filter logic.
   Reuse hotelService, apartmentService, carService, userService, authService rather than creating parallel APIs.
   UI Composition
   Building new pages from existing components in src/components/home/** and src/components/dashboard/**.
   Unacceptable (without explicit instruction)
   Cross-cutting rewrites:
   Migrating to a different router, state library, or data fetching library.
   Replacing Supabase with another backend or adding another backend client.
   Converting the project to a different framework (Next.js, Remix, etc.).
   Large-scale refactors:
   Restructuring the entire src/pages/** or src/components/** hierarchy.
   Renaming domains (Apartments → Apartments, etc.) if it breaks paths, types, or table names.
   Diverging patterns:
   Adding new API calls directly in components when a service module for that domain exists.
   Creating “utility” functions that encapsulate business logic but live in unrelated folders.
9. Rules for Modifying Existing Code vs Creating New Code
   Modify Existing Code When:
   Fixing a bug in the current behavior.
   Extending a feature that is already implemented and you need to maintain consistency.
   Making small, non-breaking enhancements (e.g., adding an optional field or behavior).
   Create New Code When:
   Implementing a new feature or page that is not conceptually the same as an existing one.
   Adding a new domain concept (with its own types, services, and pages).
   Introducing reusable UI primitives or hooks that can serve multiple pages.
   Modification Rules
   Prefer small, localized diffs:
   Do not “rewrite the file” when a small change is sufficient.
   Preserve existing formatting and style where possible.
   Keep public APIs stable:
   If you must change the shape of props or service return types, ensure all call sites are updated and the change is clearly explained.
10. Error Handling, Logging & Observability
    Services
    Follow patterns in hotelService, apartmentService, carService, userService, authService:
    Check error after Supabase calls.
    Include descriptive console.error messages with context.
    Throw errors that provide enough information to act on.
    Components & Hooks
    Expose error states via:
    React Query’s error or custom hook error state (string | null), as in useSearchFilters.
    For user-facing messages, use the existing toast mechanisms (Toaster, Sonner).
    Logging
    console.log and console.error are acceptable for debugging-style logs, but:
    Do not add noisy logging in tight loops or high-frequency code.
    When adding logs, include module context (e.g., [Car Service], [useSearchFilters]).
11. AI Agent Behavior & Change Management
    Minimal, Localized Diffs
    Always prefer the smallest change that solves the task:
    Modify only the functions or components directly involved.
    Avoid changing unrelated imports, formatting, or moving code around.
    Do not reformat entire files or apply stylistic refactors unless explicitly asked.
    Explaining Risky Changes
    Before applying any change that:
    Alters routing in App.tsx.
    Modifies apiClient, authService, or userService.
    Changes data models in src/types/\*\*.
    Changes patterns in core services (hotelService, apartmentService, carService, storageService).
    The AI agent must:
    Explain the intent, potential impact, and alternatives in natural language.
    Confirm how backward compatibility is preserved (or clearly note breaking changes if explicitly requested).
    No New Libraries/Frameworks
    Do not add new entries to dependencies or devDependencies unless:
    The user explicitly requests a new library.
    The impact and rationale are clearly documented.
    Linting & Formatting
    Respect existing lint rules from eslint.config.js.
    Do not change ESLint, TypeScript, Tailwind, Vite, or other config files unless the task requires it.
